ty and its sensitivity to the dark matter sub clumps in the context of galaxy clusters the non linear lensing probes the transitional region between strong and weak lensing and provides crucial information in the area where systematic problems dominate the weak lensing analysis alone we describe a new non parametric algorithm for the reconstruction of dark matter distribution in galaxy clusters based on both weak and non linear lensing measurements which allows us to restore the fine details of the dark matter distribution this mass reconstruction algorithm is based on the application of a general d bar inverse problem method to the non linear lensing analysis we demonstrate robustness of the method on simulated images we also applied this algorithm to reconstruction of mass distribution in the abell 1689 cluster read more kipac tea talk speaker don ellison read more kipac tea talk cancelled joint with acks seminar read more kipac tea talk cancelled read more kipac tea talk speaker hendrik hildebrandt leiden university cosmic magnification a new window to cosmology read more kipac tea talk speaker sanghamitra deb drexel university title substructure and shape of galaxy clusters abstract we present a non parametric measure of the ellipticities and alignment of the dark matter halos of the supercluster abell 901 902 this super cluster is a system of four separate peaks in a $0.5 o times0 5 o field of view we map the mass distribution of each individual peak using an improved version of pbl and measure the ellipticity of of the dark matter halos associated with two of the peaks from the mass map and by fitting them to a singular isothermal ellipse the parametric and non parametric measurements are consistent for a901b while the position angle for the southwest group is different for the two techniques we account for this discrepancy to substructure present in the southwest group a901b has an axis ratio of $0.37 pm 0.1 and the southwest group has an axis ratio of $0.54 